post_cb({"8450429": {"CommentCount": "1", "AcceptedAnswerId": "8450551", "CreationDate": "2011-12-09T19:08:03.317", "LastActivityDate": "2011-12-09T19:16:25.303", "PostTypeId": "1", "ViewCount": "2346", "FavoriteCount": "3", "Title": "Is a pointer an lvalue or rvalue?", "Id": "8450429", "Score": "3", "Body": "<p>In other post, I came across</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_8450429_8450429_0\">(5.2.9/8) An rvalue of type \"pointer to member of D of type cv1 T\" can\n  be converted to an rvalue of type \"pointer to member of B of type cv2\n  T\", where B is a base class (clause 10) of D,</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Note this from language standard. so my question,</p>\n<pre><code>int i = 0;\nint *p = &amp;i;\n*p = 1;\n</code></pre>\n<p>Is pointer an lvalue in all the cases? When does it is treated as rvalue?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><pointers>", "OwnerUserId": "1086635", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_8450429_8450429_0": {"section_id": 43, "quality": 0.6842105263157895, "length": 13}}, "n3337": {"so_8450429_8450429_0": {"section_id": 40, "quality": 0.6842105263157895, "length": 13}}, "n4659": {"so_8450429_8450429_0": {"section_id": 43, "quality": 0.6842105263157895, "length": 13}}}, "8450551": {"ParentId": "8450429", "CommentCount": "5", "Body": "<p>A pointer is not the kind of thing that can be an rvalue or an lvalue. A pointer is a <em>type</em>. The only thing that can be an rvalue or an lvalue is an <em>expression</em>.</p>\n<p>Consider this similar question: \"Is an integer an lvalue or an rvalue\". Well, neither. \"3\" is an integer, and an rvalue. \"3=i;\" is illegal. But \"i=3;\" is legal if 'i' is an integer. So 'i' is an integer and an lvalue. '3' is an integer and a rvalue.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "721269", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "8450551", "Score": "15", "CreationDate": "2011-12-09T19:16:25.303", "LastActivityDate": "2011-12-09T19:16:25.303"}});